**Sec. 100001. Applicability of the immigration laws.**
This section establishes that the new fee schedule applies to aliens in the circumstances described in the subtitle and defines terms using the Immigration and Nationality Act (8 U.S.C. 1101). It clarifies that references to specific sections within this subtitle refer to corresponding provisions of the Immigration and Nationality Act unless expressly stated otherwise. The section serves as the foundational applicability clause for the subsequent fee and funding provisions.

**Sec. 100002. Asylum fee.**
The Secretary of Homeland Security or the Attorney General must collect a fee of at least $100 from any alien filing an initial asylum application, with amounts adjusted annually for inflation starting in fiscal year 2026. Fifty percent of fees collected by the Attorney General are credited to the Executive Office for Immigration Review, while 50 percent collected by the Secretary are deposited into the Immigration Examinations Fee Account. All proceeds are retained without further appropriation, and no fee waivers or reductions are permitted.

**Sec. 100003. Employment authorization document fees.**
A fee of at least $550 is imposed on aliens filing initial applications for employment authorization, including asylum applicants, parolees, and those with Temporary Protected Status, with inflation adjustments beginning in fiscal year 2026. For asylum applicants, 25 percent of fees are credited to U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) for fraud detection, while all fees for parolees and TPS holders are deposited into the general Treasury fund. No fee waivers or reductions are allowed for any of these categories.

**Sec. 100004. Immigration parole fee.**
The Secretary of Homeland Security must charge a fee of at least $1,000 to any alien paroled into the United States, with exceptions for medical emergencies, organ donors, imminent family deaths, funerals, adopted children with medical needs, and specific law enforcement assistance cases. The fee amount is subject to annual inflation adjustments starting in fiscal year 2026, and all collected fees are deposited into the general fund of the Treasury. Fee waivers are prohibited except for the specific humanitarian and law enforcement exceptions listed.

**Sec. 100005. Special immigrant juvenile fee.**
A fee of at least $250 is required from any alien, parent, or legal guardian applying for special immigrant juvenile status under section 101(a)(27)(J) of the Immigration and Nationality Act. This fee is subject to annual inflation adjustments beginning in fiscal year 2026, and all proceeds are deposited into the general fund of the Treasury. No fee waivers or reductions are permitted for this application.

**Sec. 100006. Temporary protected status fee.**
The fee for Temporary Protected Status (TPS) applications is increased from $50 to a maximum of $500, subject to annual inflation adjustments starting in fiscal year 2026. The authority to set this fee is transferred to the Attorney General, and all collected fees are deposited into the general fund of the Treasury. Fee waivers are explicitly prohibited for TPS applicants.

**Sec. 100007. Visa integrity fee.**
A fee of at least $250 is imposed on any alien issued a nonimmigrant visa at the time of issuance, with amounts adjusted annually for inflation starting in fiscal year 2026. The Secretary of Homeland Security may reimburse this fee if the alien complied with all visa conditions and departed within five days of expiration or obtained an extension or adjustment of status. All unreimbursed fees are deposited into the general fund of the Treasury, and no waivers are allowed.

**Sec. 100008. Form I-94 fee.**
A fee of at least $24 is charged to any alien submitting an application for a Form I-94 Arrival/Departure Record, with annual inflation adjustments beginning in fiscal year 2026. Twenty percent of the collected fees are deposited into the Land Border Inspection Fee Account for U.S. Customs and Border Protection to process I-94 forms, while the remainder goes to the general Treasury fund. No fee waivers or reductions are permitted.

**Sec. 100009. Annual asylum fee.**
An annual fee of at least $100 is required from any alien whose asylum application remains pending for each calendar year, with amounts adjusted for inflation starting in fiscal year 2026. All fees collected under this section are deposited into the general fund of the Treasury. No fee waivers or reductions are allowed for pending asylum applicants.

**Sec. 100010. Fee relating to renewal and extension of employment authorization for parolees.**
A fee of at least $275 is imposed on parolees seeking renewal or extension of employment authorization, with annual inflation adjustments beginning in fiscal year 2026. Twenty-five percent of the fees are credited to USCIS and deposited into the Immigration Examinations Fee Account, while the remainder is deposited into the general Treasury fund. No fee waivers or reductions are permitted.

**Sec. 100011. Fee relating to renewal or extension of employment authorization for asylum applicants.**
A fee of not less than $275 is charged for each renewal or extension of employment authorization for asylum applicants, with employment authorization terminating immediately upon denial by an asylum officer, immigration judge, or the Board of Immigration Appeals. Twenty-five percent of the fees are credited to USCIS for the Immigration Examinations Fee Account, and the remainder goes to the general Treasury fund. No fee waivers or reductions are allowed.

**Sec. 100012. Fee relating to renewal and extension of employment authorization for aliens granted temporary protected status.**
A fee of at least $275 is required from aliens seeking renewal or extension of employment authorization based on Temporary Protected Status, with annual inflation adjustments starting in fiscal year 2026. Twenty-five percent of the fees are credited to USCIS and deposited into the Immigration Examinations Fee Account, while the remainder is deposited into the general Treasury fund. No fee waivers or reductions are permitted.

**Sec. 100013. Fees relating to applications for adjustment of status.**
This section establishes significant new fees for various immigration court proceedings, including $1,500 for adjustment of status, $1,050 for waivers of inadmissibility, $500 for TPS applications, $900 for appeals of immigration judge decisions, $900 for appeals of DHS officer decisions, $1,325 for practitioner disciplinary appeals, $900 for motions to reopen/reconsider, and $600 for suspension of deportation or cancellation of removal. Twenty-five percent of these fees are transferred from the Immigration Examinations Fee Account to the Executive Office for Immigration Review for retention and expenditure, while the remainder goes to the general Treasury fund. No fees may be used for the Legal Orientation Program, and no waivers are allowed.

**Sec. 100014. Electronic System for Travel Authorization fee.**
The fee for the Electronic System for Travel Authorization (ESTA) is increased to at least $10 for the application and $13 per travel authorization, with the fee collection period extended to October 31, 2034. Annual inflation adjustments are applied starting in fiscal year 2026. The section amends the existing statute to reflect these new amounts and the extended timeline for fee collection.

**Sec. 100015. Electronic Visa Update System fee.**
A fee of at least $30 is imposed on any alien subject to the Electronic Visa Update System (EVUS) at the time of enrollment, with annual inflation adjustments starting in fiscal year 2026. A new "CBP Electronic Visa Update System Account" is established in the Treasury to hold the difference between total fees collected and $5 multiplied by the number of payments, which is appropriated to cover CBP administrative costs. The remaining fees are deposited into the general fund of the Treasury, and no waivers are allowed.

**Sec. 100016. Fee for aliens ordered removed in absentia.**
A fee of at least $5,000 is charged to any alien ordered removed in absentia who is subsequently arrested by U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), with annual inflation adjustments beginning in fiscal year 2026. Fifty percent of the fees are credited to ICE and deposited into the Detention and Removal Office Fee Account, while the remainder goes to the general Treasury fund. The fee does not apply if the removal order was rescinded, and no waivers are permitted.

**Sec. 100017. Inadmissible alien apprehension fee.**
A fee of at least $5,000 is imposed on any inadmissible alien apprehended between ports of entry, with annual inflation adjustments starting in fiscal year 2026. Fifty percent of the fees are credited to ICE and deposited into the Detention and Removal Office Fee Account, while the remainder is deposited into the general Treasury fund. No fee waivers or reductions are allowed for this apprehension fee.

**Sec. 100018. Amendment to authority to apply for asylum.**
This section amends the Immigration and Nationality Act to change the word "may" to "shall" regarding the authority to set fees for asylum applications. It further clarifies that nothing limits the Attorney General's authority to set additional adjudication and naturalization fees in accordance with section 286(m) of the Act. This ensures the Attorney General has explicit statutory authority to implement the new fee structure.

**Sec. 100051. Appropriation for the Department of Homeland Security.**
$2,055,000,000 is appropriated to the Secretary of Homeland Security for fiscal year 2025, available through September 30, 2029, to fund immigration enforcement activities, hiring of CBP agents, removal costs, and background checks. The funds also support the collection of fingerprints and DNA from unaccompanied alien children, the return of aliens from contiguous territory, and State and local participation in ending criminal gang presence. Specific provisions include funding for the expedited removal of criminal aliens and the removal of specified unaccompanied alien children who are inadmissible and not victims of trafficking.

**Sec. 100052. Appropriation for U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement.**
$29,850,000,000 is appropriated to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) for fiscal year 2025, available through September 30, 2029, to hire and train additional personnel, including bonuses for performance, retention, and signing. The funding supports transportation for removals, information technology investments, facility upgrades, fleet modernization, and the expansion of 287(g) agreements with State and local law enforcement. It also funds the Victims of Immigration Crime Engagement Office and the Office of the Principal Legal Advisor.

**Sec. 100053. Appropriation for Federal Law Enforcement Training Centers.**
$750,000,000 is appropriated to the Federal Law Enforcement Training Centers (FLETC) for fiscal year 2025, available through September 30, 2029. At least $285,000,000 must be used for training newly hired Federal law enforcement personnel and State and local officers supporting DHS, while up to $465,000,000 can be used for facility procurement, construction, maintenance, and training equipment.

**Sec. 100054. Appropriation for the Department of Justice.**
$3,330,000,000 is appropriated to the Attorney General for the Department of Justice for fiscal year 2025, available through September 30, 2029, to hire immigration judges and support staff, with a staffing cap of 800 judges by November 1, 2028. The funds support combating drug trafficking, prosecuting immigration and gang-related crimes, and increasing funding for the Edward Byrne Memorial Justice Assistance Grant Program, which excludes community violence intervention programs. Additionally, the funds provide compensation to States for incarcerating criminal aliens and require State compliance with section 642 of the Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996.

**Sec. 100055. Bridging Immigration-related Deficits Experienced Nationwide Reimbursement Fund.**
A fund known as the "Bridging Immigration-related Deficits Experienced Nationwide (BIDEN) Reimbursement Fund" is established within the Department of Justice, with up to $3,500,000,000 appropriated for fiscal year 2025, available through September 30, 2028. The Attorney General may provide grants to States and local governments for locating and apprehending criminal aliens, investigating drug and human trafficking, court operations, and temporary criminal detention. Grants are available for completed, ongoing, or new activities occurring on or after January 20, 2021, and funds must be distributed to more than one State.

**Sec. 100056. Appropriation for the Bureau of Prisons.**
$5,000,000,000 is appropriated to the Director of the Bureau of Prisons for fiscal year 2025, available through September 30, 2029. At least $3,000,000,000 must be used for hiring and training new employees and funding salaries and benefits for the current workforce, while up to $2,000,000,000 can be used for facility maintenance and repairs.

**Sec. 100057. Appropriation for the United States Secret Service.**
$1,170,000,000 is appropriated to the Director of the United States Secret Service for fiscal year 2025, available through September 30, 2029, for additional resources, training, and technology. The funds may also be used for performance, retention, and signing bonuses for qualified agents, officers, and analysts who commit to 2 or 5 years of additional service.

**Sec. 100101. Appropriation to the Administrative Office of the United States Courts.**
$1,250,000 is appropriated for each of fiscal years 2025 through 2028 to the Director of the Administrative Office of the United States Courts. The funds are designated for continuing analyses and reporting on the state of court dockets, specifically examining the number and cost impact of judicial orders issuing non-party relief against the Federal Government.

**Sec. 100102. Appropriation to the Federal Judicial Center.**
$1,000,000 is appropriated for each of fiscal years 2025 through 2028 to the Director of the Federal Judicial Center. The funds are used to implement programs for continuing education and training for judicial branch personnel, including training on the lack of constitutional authority for legal claims seeking non-party relief against the Federal Government.

**Sec. 100201. Extension of fund.**
The Radiation Exposure Compensation Act (RECA) Fund is extended to terminate on December 31, 2028, replacing the previous 2-year termination period. This amendment ensures the Fund remains active for claims processing through the end of 2028.

**Sec. 100202. Claims relating to atmospheric testing.**
The section amends the RECA to expand eligibility for leukemia and specified disease claims related to atmospheric testing in New Mexico and Nevada, extending the covered period to November 6, 1962, and reducing the required physical presence from 2 years to 1 year. The compensation amount for leukemia claims is set at $100,000, and the amount for specified diseases is increased to $100,000. The definition of "affected area" is clarified to include specific counties in Nevada and Arizona, and claims must not have been previously paid.

**Sec. 100203. Claims relating to uranium mining.**
This section expands eligibility for uranium mining claims to include core drillers, ore transporters, and individuals involved in remediation efforts, covering a broader range of diseases including renal cancer and chronic renal disease. It introduces special rules for individuals with combined work histories in multiple positions (miner, miller, core driller, ore transporter) who worked for at least one year. The definition of "core driller" is added to clarify the scope of eligible employment.

**Sec. 100204. Claims relating to Manhattan Project waste.**
A new section (5A) is added to the RECA to provide compensation for individuals physically present in affected areas in Missouri, Tennessee, Alaska, and Kentucky for at least 2 years after January 1, 1949, who contracted specified diseases. Living claimants may receive $50,000 plus documented out-of-pocket medical expenses, while deceased claimants' surviving spouses or children may receive $25,000. The section defines specific ZIP codes as affected areas and lists covered diseases, including various cancers and leukemia.

**Sec. 100205. Limitations on claims.**
The deadline for filing claims under the Radiation Exposure Compensation Act is extended to December 31, 2027, replacing the previous deadline of 2 years after the enactment of the RECA Extension Act of 2022. This ensures that eligible individuals have a longer window to submit their claims for compensation. [end of text]


